  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/10784258b13e8c26955a3ac3f39ec916c66f0125" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:12.081ex; height:2.509ex;" alt="x_{2}=S_{2}-f"/></span><span about="#mwt231">
</span>.</p>

<figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAQI"><a href="./File:Lens3.svg" id="mwAQM"><img resource="./File:Lens3.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Lens3.svg/500px-Lens3.svg.png" data-file-width="542" data-file-height="258" data-file-type="drawing" height="238" width="500" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Lens3.svg/1000px-Lens3.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Lens3.svg/750px-Lens3.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAQQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwAQU">A camera lens forms a <i id="mwAQY">real image</i> of a distant object.</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwAQc">Therefore, if an object is placed at a distance <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt83" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>1&lt;/sub> > &apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos;"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAQg"><i>S</i><sub>1</sub> > <i>f</i></span> from a positive lens of focal length <i id="mwAQk">f</i>, we will find an image distance <i id="mwAQo">S</i><sub id="mwAQs">2</sub> according to this formula. If a screen is placed at a distance <i id="mwAQw">S</i><sub id="mwAQ0">2</sub> on the opposite side of the lens, an image is formed on it. This sort of image, which can be projected onto a screen or <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Image_sensor" title="Image sensor" id="mwAQ4">image sensor</a>, is known as a <i id="mwAQ8"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Real_image" title="Real image" id="mwARA">real image</a></i>.</p>

<figure class="mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwARE"><a href="./File:Lens3b.svg" id="mwARI"><img resource="./File:Lens3b.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Lens3b.svg/350px-Lens3b.svg.png" data-file-width="362" data-file-height="258" data-file-type="drawing" height="249" width="350" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Lens3b.svg/700px-Lens3b.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Lens3b.svg/525px-Lens3b.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwARM"/></a><figcaption id="mwARQ">Virtual image formation using a positive lens as a magnifying glass.<sup about="#mwt86" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-25" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-25"}}'><a href="./Lens_(optics)#cite_note-25" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[25]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwARU">This is the principle of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Camera" title="Camera" id="mwARY">camera</a>, and of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Human_eye" title="Human eye" id="mwARc">human eye</a>. The focusing adjustment of a camera adjusts <i id="mwARg">S</i><sub id="mwARk">2</sub>, as using an image distance different from that required by this formula produces a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Defocus_aberration" title="Defocus aberration" id="mwARo">defocused</a> (fuzzy) image for an object at a distance of <i id="mwARs">S</i><sub id="mwARw">1</sub> from the camera. Put another way, modifying <i id="mwAR0">S</i><sub id="mwAR4">2</sub> causes objects at a different <i id="mwAR8">S</i><sub id="mwASA">1</sub> to come into perfect focus.</p>

<p id="mwASE">In some cases <i id="mwASI">S</i><sub id="mwASM">2</sub> is negative, indicating that the image is formed on the opposite side of the lens from where those rays are being considered. Since the diverging light rays emanating from the lens never come into focus, and those rays are not physically present at the point where they <i id="mwASQ">appear</i> to form an image, this is called a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Virtual_image" title="Virtual image" id="mwASU">virtual image</a>. Unlike real images, a virtual image cannot be projected on a screen, but appears to an observer looking through the lens as if it were a real object at the location of that virtual image. Likewise, it appears to a subsequent lens as if it were an object at that location, so that second lens could again focus that light into a real image, <i id="mwASY">S</i><sub id="mwASc">1</sub> then being measured from the virtual image location behind the first lens to the second lens. This is exactly what the eye does when looking through a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Magnifying_glass" title="Magnifying glass" id="mwASg">magnifying glass</a>. The magnifying glass creates a (magnified) virtual image behind the magnifying glass, but those rays are then re-imaged by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lens_(anatomy)" title="Lens (anatomy)" id="mwASk">lens of the eye</a> to create a <i id="mwASo">real image</i> on the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Retina" title="Retina" id="mwASs">retina</a>.</p>

 <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r856303569" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" about="#mwt87" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"multiple image\n ","href":"./Template:Multiple_image"},"params":{"width":{"wt":"180"},"image1":{"wt":"lens4.svg"},"caption1":{"wt":"A &apos;&apos;negative&apos;&apos; lens produces a demagnified virtual image."},"image2":{"wt":"Barlow lens.svg"},"caption2":{"wt":"A Barlow lens (B) reimages a &apos;&apos;virtual object&apos;&apos; (focus of red ray path) into a magnified real image (green rays at focus)"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwASw">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class="thumb tmulti tright" about="#mwt87" id="mwAS0"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:368px;max-width:368px"><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:182px;max-width:182px"><div class="thumbimage"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Lens4.svg"><img alt="" resource="./File:Lens4.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Lens4.svg/180px-Lens4.svg.png" data-file-width="470" data-file-height="272" data-file-type="drawing" height="104" width="180" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Lens4.svg/360px-Lens4.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Lens4.svg/270px-Lens4.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left">A <i>negative</i> lens produces a demagnified virtual image.</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:182px;max-width:182px"><div class="thumbimage"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Barlow_lens.svg"><img alt="" resource="./File:Barlow_lens.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Barlow_lens.svg/180px-Barlow_lens.svg.png" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="300" data-file-type="drawing" height="90" width="180" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Barlow_lens.svg/360px-Barlow_lens.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Barlow_lens.svg/270px-Barlow_lens.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left">A Barlow lens (B) reimages a <i>virtual object</i> (focus of red ray path) into a magnified real image (green rays at focus)</div></div><div style="clear:left"></div></div></div>
<p id="mwAS4">Using a positive lens of focal length <i id="mwAS8">f</i>, a virtual image results when <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt88" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>1&lt;/sub> &lt; &apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos;"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwATA"><i>S</i><sub>1</sub> &lt; <i>f</i></span>, the lens thus being used as a magnifying glass (rather than if <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt89" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>1&lt;/sub> >> &apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos;"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwATE"><i>S</i><sub>1</sub> >> <i>f</i></span> as for a camera). Using a negative lens (<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt90" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos; &lt; 0"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwATI"><i>f</i> &lt; 0</span>) with a <i id="mwATM">real object</i> (<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt91" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>1&lt;/sub> > 0"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwATQ"><i>S</i><sub>1</sub> > 0</span>) can only produce a virtual image (<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt92" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>2&lt;/sub> &lt; 0"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwATU"><i>S</i><sub>2</sub> &lt; 0</span>), according to the above formula. It is also possible for the object distance <i id="mwATY">S</i><sub id="mwATc">1</sub> to be negative, in which case the lens sees a so-called <i id="mwATg">virtual object</i>. This happens when the lens is inserted into a converging beam (being focused by a previous lens) <i id="mwATk">before</i> the location of its real image. In that case even a negative lens can project a real image, as is done by a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Barlow_lens" title="Barlow lens" id="mwATo">Barlow lens</a>.
 </p><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303569" about="#mwt94" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"multiple image\n ","href":"./Template:Multiple_image"},"params":{"width2":{"wt":"250"},"image1":{"wt":"Reflectionprojection.jpg"},"caption1":{"wt":"Real image of a lamp is projected onto a screen (inverted). Reflections of the lamp from both surfaces of the biconvex lens are visible."},"image2":{"wt":"Convex lens (magnifying glass) and upside-down image.jpg"},"caption2":{"wt":"A convex lens ({{nowrap|&apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos; &lt;&lt; &apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>1&lt;/sub>}}) forming a real, inverted image rather than the upright, virtual image as seen in a [[magnifying glass]]"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwATs"/><div class="thumb tmulti tright" about="#mwt94" id="mwATw"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:458px;max-width:458px"><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:202px;max-width:202px"><div class="thumbimage"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Reflectionprojection.jpg"><img alt="" resource="./File:Reflectionprojection.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Reflectionprojection.jpg/200px-Reflectionprojection.jpg" data-file-width="640" data-file-height="480" data-file-type="bitmap" height="150" width="200" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Reflectionprojection.jpg/400px-Reflectionprojection.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Reflectionprojection.jpg/300px-Reflectionprojection.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left">Real image of a lamp is projected onto a screen (inverted). Reflections of the lamp from both surfaces of the biconvex lens are visible.</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:252px;max-width:252px"><div class="thumbimage"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Convex_lens_(magnifying_glass)_and_upside-down_image.jpg"><img alt="" resource="./File:Convex_lens_(magnifying_glass)_and_upside-down_image.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Convex_lens_%28magnifying_glass%29_and_upside-down_image.jpg/250px-Convex_lens_%28magnifying_glass%29_and_upside-down_image.jpg" data-file-width="4020" data-file-height="2310" data-file-type="bitmap" height="144" width="250" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Convex_lens_%28magnifying_glass%29_and_upside-down_image.jpg/500px-Convex_lens_%28magnifying_glass%29_and_upside-down_image.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Convex_lens_%28magnifying_glass%29_and_upside-down_image.jpg/375px-Convex_lens_%28magnifying_glass%29_and_upside-down_image.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left">A convex lens (<span class="nowrap"><i>f</i> &lt;&lt; <i>S</i><sub>1</sub></span>) forming a real, inverted image rather than the upright, virtual image as seen in a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Magnifying_glass" title="Magnifying glass">magnifying glass</a></div></div><div style="clear:left"></div></div></div>

<p id="mwAT0">For a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Thin_lens" title="Thin lens" id="mwAT4">thin lens</a>, the distances <i id="mwAT8">S</i><sub id="mwAUA">1</sub> and <i id="mwAUE">S</i><sub id="mwAUI">2</sub> are measured from the object and image to the position of the lens, as described above. When the thickness of the lens is not much smaller than <i id="mwAUM">S</i><sub id="mwAUQ">1</sub> and <i id="mwAUU">S</i><sub id="mwAUY">2</sub> or there are multiple lens elements (a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Compound_lens" title="Compound lens" id="mwAUc" class="mw-redirect">compound lens</a>), one must instead measure from the object and image to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Principal_plane" title="Principal plane" id="mwAUg" class="mw-redirect">principal planes</a> of the lens. If distances <i id="mwAUk">S</i><sub id="mwAUo">1</sub> or <i id="mwAUs">S</i><sub id="mwAUw">2</sub> pass through a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Medium_(optics)" title="Medium (optics)" id="mwAU0" class="mw-redirect">medium</a> other than air or vacuum a more complicated analysis is required.</p>

<section data-mw-section-id="8" id="mwAU4"><h3 id="Magnification">Magnification</h3>
<p id="mwAU8">The linear <i id="mwAVA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Magnification" title="Magnification" id="mwAVE">magnification</a></i> of an imaging system using a single lens is given by</p>

<dl id="mwAVI"><dd id="mwAVM"><span class="mwe-math-element" typeof="mw:Extension/math" about="#mwt286" data-mw='{"name":"math","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":" M = - \\frac{S_2}{S_1} = \\frac{f}{f - S_1} "}}' id="mwAVQ"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle M=-{\frac {S_{2}}{S_{1}}}={\frac {f}{f-S_{1}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>M</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <msub>
              <mi>S</mi>
              <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <msub>
              <mi>S</mi>
              <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>f</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
              <msub>
                <mi>S</mi>
                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>1</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle M=-{\frac {S_{2}}{S_{1}}}={\frac {f}{f-S_{1}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/9ba81b22aed933e15e889507aa5b4a3f5d6bc0fd" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.338ex; width:21.197ex; height:5.843ex;" alt="M=-{\frac {S_{2}}{S_{1}}}={\frac {f}{f-S_{1}}}"/></span><span about="#mwt286">
</span> ,</dd></dl>
<!--
 CAUTION TO EDITORS: This equation depends on an arbitrary sign convention
 (explained on the page). If the signs don't match your textbook, your book
 is probably using a different sign convention.
-->

<p id="mwAVU">where <i id="mwAVY">M</i> is the magnification factor defined as the ratio of the size of an image compared to the size of the object. The sign convention here dictates that if <i id="mwAVc">M</i> is negative, as it is for real images, the image is upside-down with respect to the object. For virtual images <i id="mwAVg">M</i> is positive, so the image is upright.</p>

<p id="mwAVk">Linear magnification <i id="mwAVo">M</i> is not always the most useful measure of magnifying power. For instance, when characterizing a visual telescope or binoculars that produce only a virtual image, one would be more concerned with the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Magnification#Magnification_as_a_number_(optical_magnification)" title="Magnification" id="mwAVs">angular magnification</a>—which expresses how much larger a distant object appears through the telescope compared to the naked eye. In the case of a camera one would quote the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Plate_scale" title="Plate scale" id="mwAVw">plate scale</a>, which compares the apparent (angular) size of a distant object to the size of the real image produced at the focus. The plate scale is the reciprocal of the focal length of the camera lens; lenses are categorized as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Long-focus_lens" title="Long-focus lens" id="mwAV0">long-focus lenses</a> or <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wide-angle_lens" title="Wide-angle lens" id="mwAV4">wide-angle lenses</a> according to their focal lengths.</p>

<p id="mwAV8">Using an inappropriate measurement of magnification can be formally correct but yield a meaningless number. For instance, using a magnifying glass of 5<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAWA"> </span>cm focal length, held 20<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAWE"> </span>cm from the eye and 5<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAWI"> </span>cm from the object, produces a virtual image at infinity of infinite linear size: <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt97" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;M&apos;&apos; = ∞"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAWM"><i>M</i> = ∞</span>. But the <i id="mwAWQ">angular magnification</i> is 5, meaning that the object appears 5 times larger to the eye than without the lens. When taking a picture of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moon" title="Moon" id="mwAWU">moon</a> using a camera with a 50<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAWY"> </span>mm lens, one is not concerned with the linear magnification <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt98" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;M&apos;&apos; ≈ {{val|-50|u=mm}} / {{val|380000|u=km}} = {{val|-1.3|e=-10}}."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAWc"><i>M</i> ≈ <span class="nowrap"><span style="display:none" class="sortkey">3001500000000000000♠</span>−50<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>mm</span> / <span class="nowrap"><span style="display:none" class="sortkey">7008380000000000000♠</span>380<span style="margin-left:.25em;">000</span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>km</span> = <span class="nowrap"><span style="display:none" class="sortkey">3009870000000000000♠</span>−1.3<span style="margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">×</span>10<sup>−10</sup></span>.</span> Rather, the plate scale of the camera is about 1°/mm, from which one can conclude that the 0.5<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAWg"> </span>mm image on the film corresponds to an angular size of the moon seen from earth of about 0.5°.</p>

<p id="mwAWk">In the extreme case where an object is an infinite distance away, <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt99" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>1&lt;/sub> = ∞"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAWo"><i>S</i><sub>1</sub> = ∞</span>, <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt100" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;S&apos;&apos;&lt;sub>2&lt;/sub> = &apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos;"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAWs"><i>S</i><sub>2</sub> = <i>f</i></span> and <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt101" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;M&apos;&apos; = −&apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos;/∞= 0"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAWw"><i>M</i> = −<i>f</i>/∞= 0</span>, indicating that the object would be imaged to a single point in the focal plane. In fact, the diameter of the projected spot is not actually zero, since <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diffraction" title="Diffraction" id="mwAW0">diffraction</a> places a lower limit on the size of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Point_spread_function" title="Point spread function" id="mwAW4">point spread function</a>. This is called the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diffraction_limit" title="Diffraction limit" id="mwAW8" class="mw-redirect">diffraction limit</a>.</p>

<figure class="mw-halign-none" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAXA"><a href="./File:Thin_lens_images.svg" id="mwAXE"><img resource="./File:Thin_lens_images.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Thin_lens_images.svg/500px-Thin_lens_images.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="293" data-file-type="drawing" height="286" width="500" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Thin_lens_images.svg/1000px-Thin_lens_images.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Thin_lens_images.svg/750px-Thin_lens_images.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAXI"/></a><figcaption id="mwAXM">Images of black letters in a thin convex lens of focal length <i id="mwAXQ">f</i> are shown in red. Selected rays are shown for letters <b id="mwAXU">E</b>, <b id="mwAXY">I</b> and <b id="mwAXc">K</b> in blue, green and orange, respectively. Note that <b id="mwAXg">E</b> (at 2<i id="mwAXk">f</i>) has an equal-size, real and inverted image; <b id="mwAXo">I</b> (at <i id="mwAXs">f</i>) has its image at <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Infinity" title="Infinity" id="mwAXw">infinity</a>; and <b id="mwAX0">K</b> (at <i id="mwAX4">f</i>/2) has a double-size, virtual and upright image.</figcaption></figure>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="9" id="mwAX8"><h2 id="Aberrations">Aberrations</h2>
<span about="#mwt102" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Optical aberration","href":"./Template:Optical_aberration"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYA">
</span><table class="infobox" style="font-size: smaller;" about="#mwt102">
<tbody><tr><th style="font-size:larger; background: #ccc;"><div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Template:Optical_aberration" title="Template:Optical aberration"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Template_talk:Optical_aberration" title="Template talk:Optical aberration"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Optical_aberration&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Optical_aberration" title="Optical aberration">Optical aberration</a></th></tr>
<tr>
<td><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg"><img resource="./File:Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg/40px-Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" data-file-type="drawing" height="40" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg/80px-Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg/60px-Out-of-focus_image_of_a_spoke_target..svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Defocus_aberration" title="Defocus aberration">Defocus</a><br/>
<p><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg"><img resource="./File:HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg/40px-HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg.png" data-file-width="2362" data-file-height="1890" data-file-type="drawing" height="32" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg/80px-HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg/60px-HartmannShack_1lenslet.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tilt_(optics)" title="Tilt (optics)">Tilt</a><br/>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Spherical_aberration_3.svg"><img resource="./File:Spherical_aberration_3.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Spherical_aberration_3.svg/40px-Spherical_aberration_3.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="243" data-file-type="drawing" height="19" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Spherical_aberration_3.svg/80px-Spherical_aberration_3.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Spherical_aberration_3.svg/60px-Spherical_aberration_3.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Spherical_aberration" title="Spherical aberration">Spherical aberration</a><br/>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Astigmatism.svg"><img resource="./File:Astigmatism.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Astigmatism.svg/40px-Astigmatism.svg.png" data-file-width="731" data-file-height="377" data-file-type="drawing" height="21" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Astigmatism.svg/80px-Astigmatism.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Astigmatism.svg/60px-Astigmatism.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Astigmatism_(optical_systems)" title="Astigmatism (optical systems)">Astigmatism</a><br/>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Lens_coma.svg"><img resource="./File:Lens_coma.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Lens_coma.svg/40px-Lens_coma.svg.png" data-file-width="313" data-file-height="248" data-file-type="drawing" height="32" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Lens_coma.svg/80px-Lens_coma.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Lens_coma.svg/60px-Lens_coma.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Coma_(optics)" title="Coma (optics)">Coma</a> <br/>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Barrel_distortion.svg"><img resource="./File:Barrel_distortion.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Barrel_distortion.svg/40px-Barrel_distortion.svg.png" data-file-width="768" data-file-height="768" data-file-type="drawing" height="40" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Barrel_distortion.svg/80px-Barrel_distortion.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Barrel_distortion.svg/60px-Barrel_distortion.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Distortion_(optics)" title="Distortion (optics)">Distortion</a><br/>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Field_curvature.svg"><img resource="./File:Field_curvature.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Field_curvature.svg/40px-Field_curvature.svg.png" data-file-width="415" data-file-height="250" data-file-type="drawing" height="24" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Field_curvature.svg/80px-Field_curvature.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Field_curvature.svg/60px-Field_curvature.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Petzval_field_curvature" title="Petzval field curvature">Petzval field curvature</a><br/>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg"><img resource="./File:Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg/40px-Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="308" data-file-type="drawing" height="24" width="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg/80px-Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg/60px-Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chromatic_aberration" title="Chromatic aberration">Chromatic aberration</a></p></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt103" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Optical aberration"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYE">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Optical_aberration" title="Optical aberration">Optical aberration</a></div>

<p id="mwAYI">Lenses do not form perfect images, and a lens always introduces some degree of distortion or <i id="mwAYM">aberration</i> that makes the image an imperfect replica of the object. Careful design of the lens system for a particular application minimizes the aberration. Several types of aberration affect image quality, including spherical aberration, coma, and chromatic aberration.</p>

<section data-mw-section-id="10" id="mwAYQ"><h3 id="Spherical_aberration">Spherical aberration</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt104" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Spherical aberration"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYU">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Spherical_aberration" title="Spherical aberration">Spherical aberration</a></div>

<p id="mwAYY"><i id="mwAYc">Spherical aberration</i> occurs because spherical surfaces are not the ideal shape for a lens, but are by far the simplest shape to which glass can be <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fabrication_and_testing_of_optical_components" title="Fabrication and testing of optical components" id="mwAYg">ground and polished</a>, and so are often used. Spherical aberration causes beams parallel to, but distant from, the lens axis to be focused in a slightly different place than beams close to the axis. This manifests itself as a blurring of the image. Lenses in which closer-to-ideal, non-spherical surfaces are used are called <i id="mwAYk">aspheric</i> lenses. These were formerly complex to make and often extremely expensive, but advances in technology have greatly reduced the manufacturing cost for such lenses. Spherical aberration can be minimised by carefully choosing the surface curvatures for a particular application. For instance, a plano-convex lens, which is used to focus a collimated beam, produces a sharper focal spot when used with the convex side towards the beam source.</p>

<p id="mwAYo"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image" id="mwAYs"><a href="./File:Lens5.svg" id="mwAYw"><img resource="./File:Lens5.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Lens5.svg/400px-Lens5.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="308" data-file-type="drawing" height="241" width="400" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Lens5.svg/800px-Lens5.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Lens5.svg/600px-Lens5.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAY0"/></a></figure-inline></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="11" id="mwAY4"><h3 id="Coma">Coma</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt105" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Coma (optics)"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAY8">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Coma_(optics)" title="Coma (optics)">Coma (optics)</a></div>

<p id="mwAZA"><i id="mwAZE">Coma</i>, or <i id="mwAZI">comatic aberration</i>, derives its name from the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Comet" title="Comet" id="mwAZM">comet</a>-like appearance of the aberrated image. Coma occurs when an object off the optical axis of the lens is imaged, where rays pass through the lens at an angle to the axis θ. Rays that pass through the centre of a lens of focal length <i id="mwAZQ">f</i> are focused at a point with distance <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt106" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;f&apos;&apos; [[Tangent function|tan]] θ"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAZU"><i>f</i> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tangent_function" title="Tangent function" class="mw-redirect">tan</a> θ</span> from the axis. Rays passing through the outer margins of the lens are focused at different points, either further from the axis (positive coma) or closer to the axis (negative coma). In general, a bundle of parallel rays passing through the lens at a fixed distance from the centre of the lens are focused to a ring-shaped image in the focal plane, known as a <i id="mwAZY">comatic circle</i>. The sum of all these circles results in a V-shaped or comet-like flare. As with spherical aberration, coma can be minimised (and in some cases eliminated) by choosing the curvature of the two lens surfaces to match the application. Lenses in which both spherical aberration and coma are minimised are called <i id="mwAZc">bestform</i> lenses.</p>

<p id="mwAZg"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image" id="mwAZk"><a href="./File:Lens-coma.svg" id="mwAZo"><img resource="./File:Lens-coma.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Lens-coma.svg/400px-Lens-coma.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="308" data-file-type="drawing" height="241" width="400" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Lens-coma.svg/800px-Lens-coma.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Lens-coma.svg/600px-Lens-coma.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAZs"/></a></figure-inline></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="12" id="mwAZw"><h3 id="Chromatic_aberration">Chromatic aberration</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt107" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Chromatic aberration"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAZ0">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chromatic_aberration" title="Chromatic aberration">Chromatic aberration</a></div>

<p id="mwAZ4"><i id="mwAZ8">Chromatic aberration</i> is caused by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dispersion_(optics)" title="Dispersion (optics)" id="mwAaA">dispersion</a> of the lens material—the variation of its <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Refractive_index" title="Refractive index" id="mwAaE">refractive index</a>, <i id="mwAaI">n</i>, with the wavelength of light. Since, from the formulae above, <i id="mwAaM">f</i> is dependent upon <i id="mwAaQ">n</i>, it follows that light of different wavelengths is focused to different positions. Chromatic aberration of a lens is seen as fringes of colour around the image. It can be minimised by using an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Achromatic_lens" title="Achromatic lens" id="mwAaU">achromatic doublet</a> (or <i id="mwAaY">achromat</i>) in which two materials with differing dispersion are bonded together to form a single lens. This reduces the amount of chromatic aberration over a certain range of wavelengths, though it does not produce perfect correction. The use of achromats was an important step in the development of the optical microscope. An <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Apochromat" title="Apochromat" id="mwAac">apochromat</a> is a lens or lens system with even better chromatic aberration correction, combined with improved spherical aberration correction. Apochromats are much more expensive than achromats.</p>

<p id="mwAag">Different lens materials may also be used to minimise chromatic aberration, such as specialised coatings or lenses made from the crystal <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fluorite" title="Fluorite" id="mwAak">fluorite</a>. This naturally occurring substance has the highest known <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abbe_number" title="Abbe number" id="mwAao">Abbe number</a>, indicating that the material has low dispersion.</p>

<p id="mwAas"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image" id="mwAaw"><a href="./File:Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg" id="mwAa0"><img resource="./File:Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg/400px-Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="308" data-file-type="drawing" height="241" width="400" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg/800px-Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg/600px-Chromatic_aberration_lens_diagram.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAa4"/></a></figure-inline>
<figure-inline typeof="mw:Image" id="mwAa8"><a href="./File:Lens6b-en.svg" id="mwAbA"><img resource="./File:Lens6b-en.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Lens6b-en.svg/400px-Lens6b-en.svg.png" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="320" data-file-type="drawing" height="250" width="400" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Lens6b-en.svg/800px-Lens6b-en.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Lens6b-en.svg/600px-Lens6b-en.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAbE"/></a></figure-inline></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="13" id="mwAbI"><h3 id="Other_types_of_aberration">Other types of aberration</h3>
<p id="mwAbM">Other kinds of aberration include <i id="mwAbQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Field_curvature" title="Field curvature" id="mwAbU" class="mw-redirect">field curvature</a></i>, <i id="mwAbY"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Barrel_distortion" title="Barrel distortion" id="mwAbc" class="mw-redirect">barrel</a> </i> and <i id="mwAbg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pincushion_distortion" title="Pincushion distortion" id="mwAbk" class="mw-redirect">pincushion distortion</a></i>, and <i id="mwAbo"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Astigmatism_(optical_systems)" title="Astigmatism (optical systems)" id="mwAbs">astigmatism</a></i>.</p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="14" id="mwAbw"><h3 id="Aperture_diffraction">Aperture diffraction</h3>
<p id="mwAb0">Even if a lens is designed to minimize or eliminate the aberrations described above, the image quality is still limited by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diffraction" title="Diffraction" id="mwAb4">diffraction</a> of light passing through the lens' finite <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aperture" title="Aperture" id="mwAb8">aperture</a>. A <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diffraction-limited" title="Diffraction-limited" id="mwAcA" class="mw-redirect">diffraction-limited</a> lens is one in which aberrations have been reduced to the point where the image quality is primarily limited by diffraction under the design conditions.</p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="15" id="mwAcE"><h2 id="Compound_lenses">Compound lenses</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt108" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"See also","href":"./Template:See_also"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Photographic lens"},"2":{"wt":"Doublet (lens)"},"3":{"wt":"Triplet lens"},"4":{"wt":"Achromatic lens"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAcI">See also: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Photographic_lens" title="Photographic lens" class="mw-redirect">Photographic lens</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Doublet_(lens)" title="Doublet (lens)">Doublet (lens)</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Triplet_lens" title="Triplet lens">Triplet lens</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Achromatic_lens" title="Achromatic lens">Achromatic lens</a></div>
<p id="mwAcM">Simple lenses are subject to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lens_(optics)#Aberrations" id="mwAcQ">optical aberrations</a> discussed above. In many cases these aberrations can be compensated for to a great extent by using a combination of simple lenses with complementary aberrations. A <i id="mwAcU">compound lens</i> is a collection of simple lenses of different shapes and made of materials of different refractive indices, arranged one after the other with a common axis.</p>

<p id="mwAcY">The simplest case is where lenses are placed in contact: if the lenses of focal lengths <i id="mwAcc">f</i><sub id="mwAcg">1</sub> and <i id="mwAck">f</i><sub id="mwAco">2</sub> are "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Thin_lens" title="Thin lens" id="mwAcs">thin</a>", the combined focal length <i id="mwAcw">f</i> of the lenses is given by</p>

<dl id="mwAc0"><dd id="mwAc4"><span class="mwe-math-element" typeof="mw:Extension/math" about="#mwt288" data-mw='{"name":"math","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":"\\frac{1}{f} = \\frac{1}{f_1} + \\frac{1}{f_2}."}}' id="mwAc8"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle {\frac {1}{f}}={\frac {1}{f_{1}}}+{\frac {1}{f_{2}}}.}">
